## Track 1 — Akkadian Wê-ila and the ṭēmu transferred through flesh

In **Atrahasis Tablet I, MS A iv 15** (Lambert & Millard 1969; confirmed in MB Sippar duplicate, George & Al-Rawi *Iraq* 58 [1996]), the keystone line reads:

> *ᵈwe-e i-la ša i-šu-ú ṭè-e-ma* — "Wê-ila, **a god who possessed ṭēmu**" (VH).

The Igigi revolt (lines 1–6, 21–26) describes them digging the rivers *Idiglat* (Tigris) and *Purattu* (Euphrates), bearing the *šupšikku* (corvée-basket) and *dullu* (toil). The slaughter happens "in their assembly" (*ina puḫrišunu iṭṭabḫu*); from his *šīru* (flesh) and *damu* (blood), Nintu mixes the *ṭiṭṭu* (clay), and the Anunnaki cast their *ruʾtu* (saliva/spittle) upon it. **The decisive theological line is Tablet I 213–215**: *ina šīr ili eṭemmu libši / baltu ittašu lūšēdišuma / aššum lā muššî eṭemmu libši* — "From the flesh of the god let an *eṭemmu* (ghost) come into being / let it make him know that he is alive by its sign / **so that (the slain god) be not forgotten, let the *eṭemmu* exist**" (VH).

The wordplay is deliberate and triangulated by every major Assyriologist working in French and German: **awīlu** (man) ↔ **Wê-ila** (the god's name) ↔ **eṭemmu** (ghost) ↔ **ṭēmu** (intellect). Bottéro renders *ṭēmu* in this context as **"intelligence, capacité-de-projet"** (*Lorsque les dieux faisaient l'homme*, Gallimard 1989, p. 537); Maul's chapter in *Aspekte des Menschseins* (Brill 2012) treats it as **"Verstand, Intellekt"** identified with the personal god as *Ego-Potenz*. Von Soden's AHw III col. 1385 lists the senses *Verstand, Plan, Befehl* and, uniquely for the anthropogonic context, "**Geist, das was den Menschen vom Tier unterscheidet**" — spirit, that which distinguishes man from animal. Confidence: VH on the keystone line, H on the philological consensus.

In contrast, **Enūma Eliš VI 33** (Lambert *Babylonian Creation Myths* 2013) reads simply: *ina dāmēšu ibnâ amēlūta* — "from his blood [Kingu's] he created humanity." Kingu is the *rebel commander* (VI 29: *ša ibnû tuqunta* "who fashioned strife"). **The same mechanism — divine blood transferred through clay — carries opposite theology**: Atrahasis inherits intellect from a god slain *because* he possessed *ṭēmu*; Enūma Eliš inherits rebellion-blood from a defeated insurgent.

The Sumerian **Enki and Ninmaḫ** (ETCSL 1.1.2, lines 56–78) parallels — drunken Ninmaḫ produces seven defective humans whom Enki assigns social roles: the *lú gi šu sig* (man with weak hands) becomes a royal attendant, the *gi₄-bi ĝiš-nu₁₁-gi₄-gi₄ lú u₆-e* (the blind one) receives *nam-nar* — **the art of music**; the eunuch (*lú su-ba ĝiš nu-ĝar gal₄-la nu-ĝar*) becomes *tiru* (palace courtier) "to stand before the king." Mechanism: **(c)** — capacity installed through naming and fate-decree (*nam-tar*), no flesh-and-blood transfer. The structural identity with Obatala (Track 6) is precise.

Mechanism classification for Atrahasis: **(b) divine essence transferred via material vehicle**, conserved as the persistent *eṭemmu* whose explicit function is **mnemonic** — to prevent the slain god from being forgotten.

