## Track 2 — Genesis 2:7, the cognate root n-p-ḥ, and Ramban's emanation

The Masoretic text (Leningrad B19A, 1008 CE, identical in the Aleppo Codex) reads:

> וַיִּ֩יצֶר֩ יְהֹוָ֨ה אֱלֹהִ֜ים אֶת־הָֽאָדָ֗ם עָפָר֙ מִן־הָ֣אֲדָמָ֔ה וַיִּפַּ֥ח בְּאַפָּ֖יו נִשְׁמַ֣ת חַיִּ֑ים וַֽיְהִ֥י הָֽאָדָ֖ם לְנֶ֥פֶשׁ חַיָּֽה׃ (VH)

The decisive philological fact: **וַיִּפַּח** *wayyippaḥ* is qal wayyiqtol of √נ-פ-ח n-p-ḥ "to blow," with assimilated nun. **This is the identical Semitic root of Arabic نفخ n-f-kh** in Q 15:29 وَنَفَخْتُ فِيهِ مِن رُّوحِي. Ibn Ezra explicitly notes the Arabic cognate: "וככה בלשון קדר" — "and likewise in the language of Qedar [Arabic]" (mgketer.org, VH).

The two great medieval commentators diverge sharply. **Rashi** on *wayyippaḥ* (Bereshit Rabbah 14:5): "עשאו מן התחתונים ומן העליונים, גוף מן התחתונים **ונשמה מן העליונים**" — "He made him from the lower and the upper, body from the lower, **neshamah from the upper**" (VH). **Ramban (Naḥmanides)** gives the strongest emanationist reading in Hebrew commentary: "כי הנופח באפי אחר — **מנשמתו יתן בו** … והוא רוח השם הגדול, מפיו דעת ותבונה" — "**He who blows into another's [nostrils] gives of his own neshamah into him** … and it is the spirit of the Great Name, from His mouth knowledge and understanding" (VH). This Hebrew sentence is the proximate source of the Aramaic Zoharic dictum **מאן דנפח מדיליה נפח** "*man de-nafaḥ mi-dileyh nafaḥ*" — quoted in Tanya I:2 as the warrant for the Jewish soul being "*ḥeleq Eloah mi-maʿal mammaš*" (literally a portion of God Above). Ramban explicitly maps the *neshamah* to the sefirah **Binah**; Zohar Ḥadash on Bereshit (Aramaic, hebrew.grimoar.cz) confirms: *we-ḥotema… itmar beih wa-yippaḥ be-appav nishmat ḥayyim, we-da Binah, ben Yah* — "the nose [of the cosmic Anthropos]… of it is said 'and He blew into his nostrils the breath of life,' and this is Binah, son of Yah" (VH).

Targum Onkelos crystallizes what the breath grants: *wahawat be-ʾadam le-rūaḥ memallelā* — "**it became in Adam a speaking spirit**." This locks in the link between *neshamah* and articulate language, the very faculty the Quran will tie to "the names" (Track 3).

**Genesis 3:1** plays a deliberate consonantal pun: וְהַנָּחָשׁ הָיָה עָרוּם *ʿārûm* "cunning" mirrors the עֲרוּמִּים *ʿărummîm* "naked" of 2:25 — same root ע-ר-מ. Rashi exploits the further play with אָרוּר *ʾārûr* "cursed" (3:14). The Hebrew exegetical tradition — Rashi, Ramban, Ibn Ezra, Radak, Zohar — **uniformly treats the serpent as villain**; but Ramban concedes that what is acquired through the transgression is "מדה אלהית מצד אחד" — "a divine quality from one perspective": autonomous moral will. Mechanism for Gen 2:7: **(b) emanation**, in the strongest sense in Ramban; tending toward **(c) created capacity installed** in Rashi.

