## Track 3 — The Quranic nafkha, the names, and Iblīs's species

The Quran preserves the most fully dramatized prostration narrative in any single tradition. The pivotal verse, **Q 15:29** (al-Ḥijr), is identical with **Q 38:72** (Ṣād):

> فَإِذَا سَوَّيْتُهُۥ وَنَفَخْتُ فِيهِ مِن رُّوحِى فَقَعُوا۟ لَهُۥ سَٰجِدِينَ (VH, Mushaf al-Madīna).

The verb *nafakhtu* (n-f-kh) is the exact Semitic cognate of Hebrew *wayyippaḥ*. The crucial grammatical question is the *mīn* in *min rūḥī*: partitive (emanation, a piece of God) or honorific (*iḍāfat tashrīf*)? **The Sunni and Ibadi consensus is honorific**: al-Qurṭubī states explicitly "والروح خَلْقٌ من خَلْقه أضافه إلى نفسه تشريفًا وتكريمًا؛ كقوله: أرضي وسمائي وبيتي وناقة الله وشهر الله" — "the spirit is a creature among His creatures; He attributed it to Himself as honor, like 'My earth, My heaven, My house, the she-camel of God, the month of God'" (VH). Al-Zamakhsharī (*al-Kashshāf*), reading anti-anthropomorphically as a Muʿtazilite, makes the nafkh a metaphor for the *bestowal of life* with no transferred substance.

The substrate is doubly named at Q 15:28 — **ṣalṣāl min ḥamaʾ masnūn**: *ṣalṣāl* (dry clay that *clinks* when struck, root ص-ل-ص-ل), *ḥamaʾ* (black fetid mud), *masnūn* (either "matured/changed" from س-ن-ن "to change," or "poured into a mold" — the philological dossier permits both). The mechanism is thus a sequence: **substrate (clay) → taswiya (proportioning) → nafkh (in-breathing) → sajda (angelic prostration)**.

**Q 2:31** specifies what Adam receives: وَعَلَّمَ ءَادَمَ ٱلْأَسْمَآءَ كُلَّهَا — "and He taught Adam the names, all of them." Al-Zamakhsharī's *Kashshāf* reads *al-asmāʾ kullahā* as "أسماء المسمَّيات" (names of the named things) and glosses the act as God "showing him the genera He had created, teaching him 'this is a horse, this is a camel' … and teaching him their properties and benefits, religious and worldly" (VH). The Muʿtazilite reading is therefore **comprehensive cognitive download of taxonomies**.

Ibn ʿArabī's *Fuṣūṣ al-Ḥikam*, *Faṣṣ Ādam* (ed. ʿAfīfī 1946), gives the Sufi maximal reading. Adam is **al-barzakh al-jāmiʿ** — the comprehensive isthmus holding *all* divine names; the angels hold only domain-specific names (Gabriel = the name *al-ʿAlīm* in its delivering mode, Mīkāʾīl = *al-Razzāq*, etc.). Their objection at Q 2:30 (atajʿalu fīhā man yufsidu fīhā wa-yasfiku al-dimāʾ) reflects their partial vision; Adam's display of names humiliates the partial knowers. This is the textual basis for the entire Akbarī cosmology of the Perfect Man.

**Q 18:50** is the decisive verse on Iblīs's species: كَانَ مِنَ ٱلْجِنِّ فَفَسَقَ عَنْ أَمْرِ رَبِّهِۦ — "**he was of the jinn**, and he deviated from his Lord's command." The verb *fasaqa* (root ف-س-ق) carries a remarkable concrete etymology: the lexicographers (Khalīl, Sībawayhi, *Lisān al-ʿArab*) trace it to *fasaqat al-ruṭbatu min qishrihā* — "the date burst from its skin." Iblīs's disobedience is described with a verb meaning *to split the protective envelope*. The grammatical crux (*istithnāʾ muttaṣil* vs. *munqaṭiʿ*) divides the tradition: Ṭabarī, with the early Companions, takes the exception in Q 2:34 as **connected** (Iblīs was of an angelic sub-tribe called "the jinn," created from *nār al-samūm*); al-Zamakhsharī, al-Rāzī, al-Bayḍāwī, and the entire Ibadi school (Aṭfayyash, *Himyān al-Zād*) take it as **disconnected** — confirmed by Q 55:15 (*khalaqa l-jānna min mārijin min nār*) and the canonical Muslim ḥadīth of ʿĀʾisha "*khuliqat al-malāʾikatu min nūr wa-khuliqa l-jānnu min mārijin min nār*" (VH).

The Ibadi reading via Aṭfayyash treats every reference to *rūḥī* under strict *iḍāfat tashrīf* to avoid any *ḥulūl* (incarnation) or *tajsīm* (corporealism); the Ibadi-Muʿtazilite axis is internally consistent.

The most provocative single passage in the dossier is **al-Ḥallāj's *Ṭawāsīn*, *Ṭāsīn al-Azal wa-l-Iltibās*** (Massignon ed., Paris 1913):

> «ما صحَّت الدعاوى لأحدٍ إلا لإبليس وأحمد صلعم … محبٌّ والمحبُّ مَهين … وإن منعتني عن سجوده فأنت المنيع … لا أعرف في العارفين أعرف بك مني» (VH).

Iblīs is staged as **the tragic monotheist** who reads *lā tasjudū illā lī* with absolute literalism: "I do not know among the gnostics one who knows You better than I." Al-Ḥallāj was executed in 922 CE for, among other charges, this theology. Massignon's French commentary terms him *un monothéiste tragique, l'amour fanatique d'un dévot scrupuleux jusqu'au scrupule*.

A **biological/perceptual reading of Iblīs's refusal** does exist in classical Arabic tafsīr: al-Qāshānī (d. ca. 730 AH), in *Taʾwīlāt al-Qurʾān* on Q 18:50, writes "(*كان من الجنّ*) أي من تلك القُوى الجسمانية المخفيّة في المادة، ولذلك فسق عن أمر ربه — أي بحُجُب المادة وأذيالها" — "**he was of those bodily powers concealed within matter, and therefore deviated from his Lord's command — through the veils of matter and its trains**" (VH). Iblīs's refusal becomes structural blindness, not moral choice. Ibn ʿArabī provides the cognate reading on **Q 38:75** (*li-mā khalaqtu bi-yadayya*): Adam was made with *both* divine hands (Jalāl + Jamāl); Iblīs, looking only with his fiery yad-Jalāl, was constitutionally incapable of seeing the comprehensive image.

Mechanism: **(b) divine essence under honorific attribution + (c) capacity installed** (life + the comprehensive names). The verb *nafakhtu* shares its Semitic root with Hebrew *wayyippaḥ*. **What is granted is precisely what Adam demonstrates against the angels: total nominative-cognitive scope.**

