## Track 4 — Andean null: Betanzos does not say "espíritu"

This track produced a critical correction of the project's premise. **The phrase "les dio espíritu" is not in Betanzos's *Suma y narración de los Incas* (1551), Part I, chapters 1–2, in the second Tiahuanaco creation.** Verification against the Martín Rubio edition (Atlas 1987 / Polifemo 2004, including the Palma de Mallorca chapters) shows that Viracocha **modeled in stone** (*hizo de piedra cierto número de gente*), **painted** the bultos (*ansí como yo aquí los tengo pintados*), and instructed the auxiliary viracochas to **call the peoples by voice** from their pacarinas (*fulanos salid e poblad esta tierra*). No verb of insufflation, no *espíritu*, no *ánima*, no *alma*, no *soplo* (VH for the absence).

The implicit Quechua substrate is **not** *espíritu* but the cluster *kamaq / kamay / kamasca* (Gerald Taylor, "Camay, camac et camasca dans le manuscrit quechua de Huarochiri," *Journal de la Société des Américanistes* 63 [1974]: 231–244). Taylor: *«Para el predicador cristiano eran necesarios un dios creador y un alma para salvar. Al primero, lo encontraba en el término kamac. El segundo era más problemático: se desconfiaba de los vocablos camay y camasca»* (H). Andean *kamay* is **a continuous flow of animating force**, not a single inaugural in-breathing.

The **Huarochirí Manuscript** chapters 1–5 — the only long pre-conquest narrative in Quechua — contains **no breath-into-clay episode**. Pre-existing humans are simply *there*; Cuniraya Viracocha is invoked as *runa kamaq, pacha kamaq* ("animator of the human, animator of the world/time"), but no insufflation scene exists. This is **VH-confidence NULL data** and it constrains every diffusionist reading of Spanish colonial chronicles: the breath motif in Sarmiento or Molina is most parsimoniously read as evangelical translation, not indigenous retention.

The **Coricancha cosmogram** of Pachacuti Yamqui Salcamayhua (ca. 1613, ed. Duviols & Itier, IFEA/CBC 1993) does include a formless oval at the apex inscribed *Viracochan pachayachachi[c]* with the surrounding legend *cay cari cachun, cay huarmi cachun* ("let this be male, let this be female"). The fashionability of identifying this as a pre-Columbian residue collapses on Duviols's demonstration: the disposition replicates a Catholic *retablo*, the surrounding fauna-flora list reproduces verbatim the **Doctrina Christiana** of the Third Council of Lima (1583), and the male/female formula is a calque of **Genesis 1:27**. Mechanism: **(b) creation by word — but Catholic-overlay (Layer C)**, not a recovered Andean form. César Itier qualifies this slightly: the *abstract* oval may preserve a residue of the *océano-Viracocha* image, incompatible with Christian anthropomorphism.

Net Andean classification: **NULL for breath-into-vessel**, with confidence VH. The Andean animation principle is *kamay* (continuous flow), not *nefesh/rūḥ/ṯꜣw* (installed quantum).

