## Track 5 — K'iche' Maya: the missing k'ux and the inverted soplo

The Popol Wuj (Ximénez MS, Newberry Ayer 1515, ca. 1701–03; modern K'iche' edition Sam Colop 1999) traces four creation attempts. The first three fail; the fourth succeeds. **None involves a breath-into-clay episode.** The verbs are *tz'aq* (to construct) and *b'it* (to mold a vessel), not anything cognate to *nafkh*.

The diagnostic passage is the third attempt's failure (Ximénez fol. 3v–4r, Sam Colop 1999 p. 34):

> *Ma k'u ja b'i kik'ux, / ma pu ja b'i kina'oj; / mawi na'tal kajtz'aq, kajb'it. / Xa loq' xeb'inik, xechakanik. / Mawi xkina'taj chik ri Uk'ux Kaj.* (VH)

"**There was nothing of their k'ux** (heart/core/essence); **nothing of their na'oj** (mind/memory); / they did not remember their Constructor, their Former. / They merely walked, they merely crawled. / They no longer remembered the Corazón del Cielo." The wooden manikins (*poy ajam che'*) **lack precisely *k'ux* — the very morpheme that names the divine center** (*Uk'ux Kaj* "Heart of Sky," *Uk'ux Ulew* "Heart of Earth"). The vessel without inner light is therefore named with a **negation of cosmic participation**: they have no center, where Heaven and Earth do.

The fourth, successful creation uses no breath either: the humans are *xa ixim utyo'jil* — "**only maize was their flesh**." K'iche' antropogony is **substantialist, not pneumatic**: the right *substance* carries the *k'ux*, no insufflation required.

What is most striking, however, is the **inversion of the breath motif** in the immediately following passage. The maize people see too clearly — *xutzin kimuqub'al ronojel uxe' kaj, chuwach ulew* ("their vision was perfected over all under the sky, on the face of the earth"). The gods then **breathe on them** to limit them:

> *Ta xmuqu kib'aq' uwach rumal Uk'ux Kaj. Xmoyik kiwach **keje' chuwach lemo' kasaqir uxe'**.* (VH)

"Then their eyeballs were covered by Heart of Sky. **Their faces were misted as when one breathes on the face of a mirror.**" The simile is unmistakable: the same gesture (divine breath on the human face) that *vivifies* in Genesis and the Quran here **occludes**. Popol Wuj inverts the topos at the structural level.

Mechanism: **NULL for breath-as-vivification; PRESENT as breath-as-limitation**. Confidence VH.

