## Track 6 — Yoruba: the two-step that exactly mirrors the Semitic complex

Yoruba primary sources (Wande Abimbọla's *Ìjìnlẹ̀ Ohùn Ẹnu Ifá* corpus; oríkì Obàtálá collected by Verger 1957) preserve an explicitly **two-step anthropogony**:

> *Obàtálá ní ó ṣe ara, Olódùmarè ní ó fi ẹ̀mí sí i* — "Obàtálá makes the body (*ara*); Olódùmarè installs the breath (*ẹ̀mí*) in it" (H; canonical formula in Yoruba philosophical literature, derived from Idowu and Abimbọla's oral collection).

Obàtálá molds humans from *amọ̀* (clay) at Ilé-Ifẹ̀, becomes drunk on *emu / ọtí ọ̀pẹ* (palm wine), and produces *àfín* (albinos), *abuké* (hunchbacks), *aró* (paralytics), *afọ́jú* (blind), *odi* (deaf-mute), *arara* (dwarves), *amúkùn-ún* (lame), who become **eni òrìṣà** (people of the òrìṣà) — sacred, under his protection, with palm wine becoming the consequent *èèwọ̀* (taboo) for his cult. Verger's *Notes sur le culte des Orisa et Vodun* (IFAN Dakar Mémoire 51, 1957) documents the ethnographic complex; Bastide's *Candomblé de Bahia* (1958) traces it intact to Brazilian Oxalá worship.

**The structural identity with Enki-Ninmaḫ is precise across at least five features** — drunkenness of demiurge, clay substrate, seven (Sumerian) / seven (Yoruba) categories of defect, social-role assignment for each, post-event taboo (implicit in Sumerian, explicit Yoruba). French Africanist scholarship (Verger, Maupoil, Bastide, Cheikh Anta Diop) does *not* posit transmission. The chronology — Enki-Ninmaḫ ca. 3rd millennium BCE; Yoruba-Arab contact post-10th c. CE; absence in adjacent Fon — falsifies a trans-Saharan diffusion hypothesis. **Convergent invention** is the best-supported reading, possibly drawing on a universal "drunkenness narrates abnormality" cognitive template. Mechanism: **(b)** — modeling + installed breath, in two agencies.

