## Track 7 — Egypt: the breath of life that is made, not blown

The closest Egyptian parallel is the **Instruction of Merikare** (Papyrus Leningrad 1116A vso, lines 130–138, ed. Helck 1977 / Quack 1992; French trans. Vernus, *Sagesses de l'Égypte pharaonique*, 2001):

> *zꜣw-tw rmṯ ꜥw.t nṯr / jr.n=f p.t tꜣ n jb=sn / dr.n=f snk n mw / **jr.n=f ṯꜣw n ꜥnḫ n fnḏ=sn** / snn.w=f pr.w m ḥꜥ.w=f* (VH)

"Humans, the cattle of God (*ꜥw.t nṯr*), are well-provided for. / He made heaven and earth for their hearts. / He drove off the avidity of the water. / **He made the breath of life for their nostrils.** / They are his images, gone out from his body."

**The verb is *jrj* "to make," not *nfj* / *sṯj* "to blow."** Egyptian preserves the noun-cluster (breath, life, nostrils) but not the *act* of insufflation. The *ṯꜣw* is created as a cosmic element available *for* the nostrils, parallel to making heaven *for* hearts. Quack (*Studien zur Lehre für Merikare*, 1992, pp. 187ff.) and Vernus emphasize this gap: the closest Egyptian parallel falls short of being the same myth.

The Heliopolitan tradition (Coffin Texts 80, 714, 1130 in de Buck's edition, French trans. Barguet 1986 and Carrier 2004) deploys an entirely different mechanism: humans emerge from the *tears* of Re (with the Egyptian pun *rmṯ* "humans" / *rmw.t* "tears"):

> *sḫpr-n=j nṯr.w m fd.t=j / jw rmṯ m rmw.t jr.t=j* — "I created the gods from my sweat; humans are from the tears of my eye" (CT VII 464f–465a, VH).

Khnum at Esna molds humans on the potter's wheel (*qd rmṯ.w*, *nb nḥp*) — pure modeling, no breath. The Memphite Theology gives creation by *jb* (heart) and *ns* (tongue) — pure word. **No single Egyptian text combines clay-modeling + nostril-insufflation + breath-of-life**; each cosmogonic center supplies one element. Mechanism: distributed across **(b)** (tears, emanation), **(a)** (Khnum modeling), and *Logos* (Memphis). The Egyptian complex is *not* the source of the Genesis/Quran complex; it is a sibling family.

