## Track 8 — Buddhism: structural absence, with a positive counter-cosmogony

The **Aggañña Sutta** (Dīgha Nikāya 27, PTS III 80–98, VH) describes beings (*sattā*) descending (*cavitvā… āgacchanti*) from the **Ābhassara** (radiant) realm: originally *manomayā, pītibhakkhā, sayampabhā, antalikkhacarā, subhaṭṭhāyino* — mind-made, joy-feeding, self-luminous, sky-traveling, glory-abiding. The *rasapathavī* (earth-savor) appears like cream on cooling milk; one being tastes it; craving (*taṇhā cassa okkami*) enters; luminosity disappears; sun, moon, and stars appear; bodies coarsen; sex differentiation arises; agriculture, theft, kingship emerge.

**There is no demiurge, no clay, no vessel, no breath, no first couple, no instantaneous origination.** The cosmos is *anamatagga* — "without discoverable beginning" (Saṃyutta-Nikāya II.178). The Abhidharmakośa-bhāṣya III (Vasubandhu, French trans. La Vallée Poussin 1923–31) repeats the schema in Sanskrit: *vidyate na tu kena cit sṛṣṭam* — "it exists but is created by no one." The Mahāvastu i.338–348 (Senart, 1882–97) gives the Lokottaravāda parallel.

Buddhism programmatically refutes *issaranimmāṇavāda* (creator-doctrine) at DN 1, MN 49, AN 3.61. Searches of the Kangyur for any *srog ʾjug* ("life-installation") in cosmogonic context return null — the term appears only in tantric statue-consecration (*rab gnas*).

**This null is the decisive datum against any cognitive-universal hypothesis** for the breath-into-vessel pattern. A literate civilization with millennia of scholastic refinement and detailed anthropogonic narratives produced an entirely different template (luminous devolution by craving) — and indeed Aggañña explicitly polemicizes against the Brahmanical *mukhato jātā* ("born from the mouth of Brahmā," Puruṣasūkta RV 10.90), which is itself the Vedic vessel-cognate. The pattern is **areal-cultural** (West Asian / Mediterranean / Saharan / partially Andean), not panhuman.

